mpairment, diabetes, old age, severe or worsening heart failure, dehydration, or concomitant therapy with other agents that increase serum potassium such as nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs, beta-blockers, cyclosporine, heparin, tacrolimus, and trimethoprim.', 'Major', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/96334/', '[1] Walmsley RN, White GH, Cain M, McCarthy PJ, Booth J "Hyperkalemia in the elderly." Clin Chem 30 (1984): 1409-12[2] Jarman PR, Mather HM "Diabetes may be independent risk factor for hyperkalaemia." BMJ 327 (2003): 812[3] Obialo CI, Ofili EO, Mirza T "Hyperkalemia in congestive heart failure patients aged 63 to 85 years with subclinical renal disease." Am J Cardiol 90 (2002): 663-5[4] Jarman PR, Kehely AM, Mather HM "Hyperkalaemia in diabetes: prevalence and associations." Postgrad Med J 71 (1995): 551-2[5] "Product Information. Cozaar (losartan)." Merck & Co, Inc, West Point, PA.[6] Large DM, Carr PH, Laing I, Davies M "Hyperkalaemia in diabetes mellitus--potential hazards of coexisting hyporeninaemic hypoaldosteronism." Postgrad Med J 60 (1984): 370-3[7] Perazella MA "Drug-induced hyperkalemia: old culprits and new offenders." Am J Med 109 (2000): 307-14[8] "Product Information. Diovan (valsartan)." Novartis Pharmaceuticals, East Hanover, NJ.[9] Perazella MA, Mahnensmith RL "Hyperkalemia in the elderly: drugs exacerbate impaired potassium homeostasis." J Gen Intern Med 12 (1997): 646-56[10] Lawson DH "Adverse reactions to potassium chloride." Q J Med 43 (1974): 433-40[11] Lawson DH, O''Connor PC, Jick H "Drug attributed alterations in potassium handling in congestive cardiac failure." Eur J Clin Pharmacol 23 (1982): 21-5[12] "Product Information. Diovan (valsartan)." Novartis Pharmaceuticals, East Hanover, NJ.[13] "Product Information. Cozaar (losartan)." Merck & Co, Inc, West Point, PA.', 'Amlodipine, Sacubitril, Hydrochlorothiazide, Nebivolol', NULL, 1767369485);
